transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for participating in this interview. I'm going to ask you some questions about your health and experiences. Let's begin.

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for having me. I'm glad to be here and share my experiences. Please feel free to ask your questions.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me a bit about yourself and your current life situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Sure! As I mentioned, my name is Hannah. I'm 35 years old and I live in suburban Chicago with my husband and our three kids. I’m a stay-at-home mom, which keeps me pretty busy with the kids. We have a middle-income household, and I rely on Medicaid for our healthcare coverage. Life can get hectic, but I try to manage everything as best as I can. My health hasn’t been the best lately, especially with chronic neck pain that I’ve been dealing with for a while. I also don’t get out much, and I know I should probably be more active, but it’s hard to find the time. Overall, I’m just trying to take care of my family and myself.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your pregnancy or pregnancies? When did you first learn you were pregnant?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Of course! I found out I was pregnant for the first time when I was 24. It was a bit of a surprise, but we were excited. I remember taking a home pregnancy test and then calling my husband right away to share the news. I had three pregnancies in total, all of which were vaginal deliveries. The last one was about five years ago, and since then, I’ve decided not to have any more children. I’m currently using barrier contraception to make sure of that. Each pregnancy had its own challenges, but I think I managed pretty well overall. 

Interviewer: That’s great to hear that you managed well. Can you share more about the prenatal care you received during your pregnancies? How did you find the experience?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: When did you first seek prenatal care? What was that experience like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I first sought prenatal care pretty early in my first pregnancy, around the sixth week. I was really eager to make sure everything was going well for the baby. I remember feeling a mix of excitement and nervousness when I went to my first appointment. The clinic was a bit busy, and I had to wait longer than I expected, which made me anxious. 

Once I finally saw the doctor, they were really nice and answered all my questions, which helped ease my worries. They did all the usual checks—weight, blood pressure, and ultrasound—to make sure everything was progressing normally. However, I did feel like I could have used more time to discuss my concerns, especially since it was my first pregnancy. 

For my subsequent pregnancies, I went to the same clinic, but I noticed that the care felt a bit rushed. I think it was just the way the appointments were scheduled. With three kids, I definitely had my hands full, and sometimes it felt hard to get the attention I needed. I often left feeling like I had more questions than answers. 

Would you like to know how the experience varied between each pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who is providing your prenatal care? Can you describe your relationship with your healthcare provider?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I received prenatal care from a local clinic that had several doctors and midwives. I mostly saw a particular doctor who seemed to be there for most of my appointments. I appreciated that he was friendly and knowledgeable, but I sometimes felt like there were so many patients that he couldn’t spend as much time with me as I would have liked. 

I think I built a decent rapport with him, but I always wished I could have had a bit more one-on-one time to discuss my specific concerns, especially since I was a first-time mom at the time. With each pregnancy, I felt like I had to adjust to different doctors or practitioners at the clinic because of the busy schedule, which made it hard to feel completely comfortable. 

If I had a specific concern, like my chronic neck pain or any other issue, it sometimes felt like I had to bring it up myself, rather than it being addressed in my appointments. Overall, the relationship was okay, but I think more continuity and personalization in care would have made a big difference for me.

Do you want me to go into more detail about how my health issues were handled during those appointments?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How often do you have prenatal appointments? Can you walk me through what a typical visit is like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I typically had prenatal appointments every four weeks during the first trimester and then more frequently as I got closer to my due date—like every two weeks and then weekly in the final month. A typical visit usually started with me checking in at the front desk and waiting in the waiting room, which was often busy. I would usually wait for about 30 minutes or more before being called back.

Once in the exam room, a nurse would take my weight and blood pressure and ask a few general questions about how I was feeling. After that, I'd wait for the doctor to come in. When the doctor arrived, they would go over my health history, do a quick physical exam, and often perform an ultrasound to check on the baby. They would listen to the heartbeat and measure my belly to see how the baby was growing.

While I appreciated these checks, I often felt like the conversation was a bit rushed. I’d have a few questions prepared, but sometimes it felt like I didn’t have enough time to ask everything I wanted. I remember feeling anxious about my chronic neck pain, especially since it was something I had been dealing with for a while. I would bring it up, but it often felt secondary to the pregnancy-related questions.

After the check-up, they would schedule the next appointment and remind me about what to expect in the coming weeks. I appreciated that they always provided some educational materials about pregnancy and what to expect, but I often wished for more time to discuss my personal situation.

Would you like to hear more about any specific aspects of these appointments or how I felt about them?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you experienced any health concerns or complications during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I did have some health concerns during my pregnancies, though thankfully, nothing too severe. I experienced some complications related to my chronic neck pain, which was challenging to manage while pregnant. Sometimes the pain would flare up, and I found it difficult to find comfortable positions, especially as my body changed. I brought this up during my appointments, but it often felt like it wasn't prioritized since they were focused on the pregnancy itself. 

There were also moments of anxiety about my overall health and how it could affect my pregnancy. I remember worrying about how my lifestyle, like my occasional smoking and limited physical activity, might impact my babies. I tried to cut back on smoking during my pregnancies, but it was tough, especially with the stress of being a mom to three kids. 

In terms of pregnancy-related complications, I did have some mild gestational hypertension during my second pregnancy, which required extra monitoring. It was a bit scary because I had to visit the clinic more frequently, and I felt the pressure to manage my stress and health better. The staff was supportive, but I still felt overwhelmed at times.

Overall, while I had some concerns, I was fortunate that my pregnancies progressed without major complications. Do you want to know how my healthcare providers addressed these issues, or is there something else you would like me to elaborate on?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What medications or supplements are you currently taking?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I'm currently not taking any medications specifically for my chronic neck pain, as I've been managing it with over-the-counter pain relievers like ibuprofen when it gets really uncomfortable. I try to limit my use of those because I’m aware of the importance of being cautious about medications, especially after having my kids. 

I also take a prenatal vitamin occasionally, even though I'm not currently pregnant. I feel like it helps me with my overall health, especially since I want to make sure I'm getting enough nutrients while I'm busy with the kids. 

I haven’t been consistent with a daily routine of vitamins or supplements, though, so I know I could do better in that area. Would you like to know more about how I make decisions regarding my health and medications?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your diet and nutrition during pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I tried to focus on eating healthy for the sake of my babies. I aimed for a balanced diet with fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and proteins, but it wasn't always easy to stick to that, especially with three kids to care for. I often found myself grabbing whatever was quick and easy, which sometimes meant less nutritious meals.

In the beginning, I was really motivated to eat well, and I would plan meals ahead of time. I tried to incorporate more fruits and vegetables, and I made sure to drink plenty of water. However, as the pregnancies progressed and life got busier, I found it challenging to maintain that balance. There were days when I relied on convenience foods and snacks that weren't the healthiest options, especially when the kids were demanding my attention.

I also experienced some cravings during my pregnancies, which sometimes led me to indulge in things like ice cream or salty snacks. I tried not to feel too guilty about it since I thought it was normal, but I did worry about how it might affect my health and the baby's development. 

I remember one of my doctors suggesting I keep a food diary to help me stay on track, which I found helpful in the beginning, but I didn't keep up with it for long. I think having more support or guidance about nutrition would have made a difference, especially with my busy lifestyle.

Would you like to hear more about how I managed my diet while juggling everything, or is there another area you want to explore?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How have you been feeling emotionally during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I experienced a mix of emotions. At the beginning, there was a lot of excitement and joy at the thought of bringing a new life into the world. However, as the pregnancies progressed, I also faced feelings of anxiety and stress. Being a mom to three kids already meant I had a lot on my plate, and I often worried about how I would manage everything once the new baby arrived.

There were days when I felt overwhelmed, especially when dealing with my chronic neck pain. It was physically and mentally taxing, and I sometimes found it difficult to cope with the demands of pregnancy alongside parenting. I also had moments of self-doubt, questioning whether I was doing everything right for my growing family.

I tried to lean on my husband for support, and he was great at helping me when I needed it. Still, I think I would have benefited from more emotional support from healthcare providers during my appointments. Sometimes, it felt like the focus was entirely on the physical aspects of the pregnancy, and I wished there was more room for discussing my emotional well-being.

Postpartum, I did experience some feelings of sadness and maybe what you would call the “baby blues.” It was a lot to juggle, and while I was grateful for my children, I found it challenging to adjust to the changes in my life and body. I think having more resources or support systems in place would have made a significant difference in how I felt emotionally during and after my pregnancies.

Would you like to know more about specific coping strategies I used or how I managed my emotional health during that time?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who supports you during your pregnancy? Can you tell me about your support network?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, my main support came from my husband, which I’m really grateful for. He was there for me through the ups and downs, helping out with the kids and trying to ease my stress whenever he could. I also had my family, especially my mom, who was a great help. She would come over to help with the kids, especially during the later stages of my pregnancies when I was feeling more uncomfortable.

My friends were supportive too, but I didn’t lean on them as much as I probably should have. Most of them were busy with their own lives and families, so while we would chat and share experiences, I didn't want to burden them with my struggles. I think I sometimes felt isolated, especially when I was dealing with my chronic pain or emotional challenges.

I also tried to connect with other moms in the area, which was nice. We would share tips and support each other, but I didn’t always have the time to attend group meet-ups or activities. I often wished I had more access to community resources or support groups, especially for moms dealing with similar challenges.

Overall, my husband and family were my main pillars of support, but I think having more structured support, like from healthcare providers or community programs, would have made a difference in how I navigated my pregnancies. Would you like to explore more about how I managed these relationships or any specific challenges I faced with my support network?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about your birth plan? What are your preferences for delivery?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I did think about my birth plan, but it was never something I put down on paper. I always knew I wanted to have vaginal deliveries since that’s how my first two went, and I had positive experiences with those births. I preferred to go into labor naturally, and I hoped for a calm environment during delivery, with my husband by my side for support.

For my last pregnancy, I remember discussing my preferences with my doctor during my appointments. I wanted to avoid unnecessary interventions unless absolutely necessary, and I was open to using pain management options if needed, depending on how things went. I wanted to try to have a relatively straightforward delivery, but I also understood that things could change quickly, especially since I was dealing with chronic neck pain. 

I think having a more concrete birth plan would have helped me feel more prepared and empowered, but with everything going on, it sometimes felt overwhelming to think about all the details. I also wished I could have had more discussions with my healthcare provider about what to expect during labor and delivery, especially since each birth can be different.

Would you like to know more about any specific aspects of my birth experiences or how I felt about the overall process?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What sources of information have you used to learn about pregnancy and childbirth?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I relied on a mix of sources to learn about pregnancy and childbirth. One of the primary resources was my healthcare provider. I would ask questions during my appointments, and they provided some educational materials, which I found helpful. However, sometimes I felt like I needed more detailed information than what was covered during those visits.

I also turned to books and online resources. I read a couple of popular pregnancy books that my friends recommended, which helped me understand what to expect week by week. Websites like the Mayo Clinic and What to Expect were also valuable for finding information about pregnancy symptoms, nutrition, and labor. I appreciated the forums where other moms shared their experiences, although I sometimes felt overwhelmed by the amount of information available online.

Additionally, I would occasionally watch videos about childbirth, which I found helpful in visualizing the process. However, with everything going on in my life, I often struggled to find the time to dedicate to learning as much as I wanted to.

I think having a more structured approach to education, like attending prenatal classes or workshops, would have been beneficial. Unfortunately, my schedule with the kids made it difficult to commit to those types of programs.

Would you like to know more about how I incorporated this information into my pregnancy journey or how I felt about the quality of the information I received?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How are you managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, managing the financial aspects was definitely a concern for us. Since I rely on Medicaid for healthcare coverage, many of my prenatal visits and necessary tests were covered, which was a relief. However, there were still other costs associated with preparing for a baby, like buying baby supplies, clothes, and other essentials. 

I tried to budget as best as I could, but with three kids already, expenses were always tight. I often looked for sales and used coupons whenever I could to save money on baby items. I also found myself reaching out to family and friends for hand-me-downs, which helped a lot. It was nice to receive things from those who had recently had babies, and it took some pressure off our budget.

When it came to planning for medical expenses, I made sure to keep track of co-pays and any out-of-pocket costs for things like ultrasounds or additional tests. I sometimes worried about how our finances would stretch once the new baby arrived, especially with the added costs of childcare and other necessities.

I think it would have been helpful to have more resources or guidance on financial planning for pregnancy and childcare. I didn't really know where to turn for advice, and sometimes I felt lost in figuring out how to manage everything. Having support or workshops focused on these aspects could have made a difference in how I felt about the financial side of preparing for a baby.

Would you like to hear more about specific challenges I faced financially during my pregnancies or how I managed the budgeting process?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How has your pregnancy affected your work or employment situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, my work situation changed quite a bit. As I mentioned earlier, I’m a stay-at-home mom, so I wasn’t employed during my pregnancies. However, I think about how my situation might have been different if I had been working outside the home. 

When I found out I was pregnant for the first time, I was actually working part-time. But as my pregnancy progressed and I had to manage the physical demands of carrying a child along with my job, it became clear that it would be challenging to balance both. I ultimately decided to leave my job to focus on my health and the pregnancy, which was a tough decision since I enjoyed my work and the extra income was helpful.

With each subsequent pregnancy, I continued to stay home full-time. It was important for me to be present for my kids, especially as they were growing up. I worried about how I would manage everything once the new baby arrived, and I felt that being at home would allow me to focus on their needs and my health.

Financially, being a stay-at-home mom had its challenges. While I appreciated the time with the kids, it also meant we had to stick to a stricter budget. I often thought about how I might eventually want to return to work, but I wanted to wait until my kids were a bit older and more independent.

I believe having more support or resources for moms who are navigating work and pregnancy could be beneficial. It can be a real struggle to balance everything, and I think many women face similar decisions. Would you like to know more about my thoughts on returning to work or how my pregnancies influenced my future career plans?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about the postpartum period? What plans do you have for after the baby arrives?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I did think about the postpartum period, and I tried to prepare myself for what to expect after delivering. I knew that the adjustment to having a new baby, along with my other children, would be challenging. I often thought about how I would manage the recovery process while also caring for my three kids.

I hoped to have some help in those early weeks after the baby arrived. My mom was always willing to step in, and I planned to lean on her support as much as possible. I also discussed with my husband how we could share the responsibilities of caring for the newborn and the other kids to make the transition smoother.

I was aware that the postpartum period could be emotionally taxing, especially with the changes happening in my body and life. I had heard about the “baby blues” and postpartum depression, so I tried to keep an open line of communication with my husband about how I was feeling. I wanted to make sure I had someone to talk to if I started feeling overwhelmed.

In terms of physical recovery, I knew I would need to take it easy and allow myself time to heal. I wanted to focus on self-care and not feel guilty about needing rest, especially with my chronic neck pain. I also thought about how I could gradually ease back into some form of exercise once I felt ready, as I knew it would be important for my overall well-being.

Overall, I hoped to create a supportive environment for myself and my family during the postpartum period, but I also recognized that it might not go as smoothly as I envisioned. Having more resources or support systems in place for new moms could have made me feel more prepared. 

Would you like to know more about any specific concerns I had for the postpartum period or how I planned to navigate that time?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Thank you for your time and for sharing your experiences with me. This concludes our interview.
